Can the euro be fixed?
Paris - Germany's Finance Minister Schäuble recently put the option of Greece leaving the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major discussion about the principles underlying the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal was put forward, European leaders had already taken note of a report on the future of the euro written by Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece led many policymakers to believe that it was necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens were questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can a consensus be reached on Greece's future?
Money is like a nation, and establishing it requires a myth.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political cost Germany paid to France for reunification.
In fact, Germany's reunification was merely the final step of an initiative that had taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing dilemma.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with the single market; at the same time, they are unwilling to maintain the monetary system dominated by the German central bank for an extended period.
A genuine European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
Looking back, Germany's reunification turned out to be more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was in severe difficulty; France was undervalued and its economy was experiencing prosperity.
Over the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark still be overvalued?
Will the countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reforms be more or less?
Establishing a reverse analysis baseline to assess the euro's impact is impossible.
But this is by no means a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone's economic performance has been consistently disappointing, and its political system must be held accountable for this.
What is truly important is whether the common European currency will still be significant in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone disintegrates during a crisis, exacerbating mutual rivalries among member states, the costs would increase even further).
In addition, the abolition of the euro may unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke of the University of Oxford has recently pointed out that this view is insufficient.
In logic, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should remain married because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still have meaning?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that the monetary union could promote economic integration and strengthen Europe's long-term growth.
In contrast, trade and investment growth within the eurozone has been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone beyond monetary unification to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the power they still possess.
This may make political sense, but it is economically nonsensical: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, so it would be a grave mistake to waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hoped the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely realized.
The euro's international use ranks second to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believe that the institutions underlying the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the policy level of Europe as a whole is inherently higher than that of individual countries.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test emerged: the eurozone overemphasized the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in a performance that lagged behind that of the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, it must further implement reforms to the policy system.
But the formulation and implementation of a schedule must have a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
Meanwhile, the ongoing debate over Greece indicates that Europe is still far from reaching consensus: the participating countries offer contradictory analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to conflicting remedies.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was significantly hindered by the differing transmission patterns across countries.
Countries favor collective action but are unable to form a unified plan because they disagree on how diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the issue the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this issue is not insurmountable, as major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of a banking union have demonstrated this.
The lack of consensus has not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, indicating that institutional governance is indeed crucial.
However, the fact that reforms and actions have only recently begun and were implemented under severe crisis pressure has made the participants清醒地 recognize the difficulty of reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer delay and pretend.
Eurozone member states must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reforms to transform the monetary union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will be doomed to repeated debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders have a duty to clarify what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to trade in exchange for what they want.
